      "value": "San Ysidro Elementary is a mid-sized elementary (K-6) district in the South region of San Diego County, near the border. About 770 of its students have an IEP, and 265 of them \u2014 roughly 34% \u2014 have an autism (ASD) eligibility, the largest autism share among districts in this directory. Around 20% of those autistic students spend most of the school day in a general-education classroom."
    },
    "what_this_means_for_parents": {
      "ai_disclaimer": "This summary was written by an AI model from the data points in this profile. The underlying numbers come from public California government sources, but the narrative is AI-written and may contain inaccuracies. Verify specific claims directly with the school district before making decisions.",
      "ai_generated": true,
      "ai_generated_at": "2026-05-18T18:47:16Z",
      "ai_model": "claude-opus (via Claude Code session)",
      "based_on_sources": [
        "cde_spedps",
        "cde_enrollment",
        "ca_dashboard",
        "ocr",
        "oah"
      ],
      "value": "About 20% of autistic students in this district are in a general-education classroom for most of the day, with around 1% in a fully separate setting, so most spend a substantial part of the day in specialized settings. Among all students with disabilities, a broader group than autism alone, 43% are in general-education classrooms most of the day. On 2024-25 state tests, students with disabilities scored about 114 points below standard in English and 135 below in math, while students overall were 36 and 62 points below. Students with disabilities were chronically absent at about 36% (compared with 29% for all students) and suspended at about 3%."
    }
  },
